<HEADLINE>
<P>
SCHULER TO INTERVIEW FOR POST WITH CLIPPERS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SCOTT HOWARD-COOPER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Mike Schuler, the National Basketball Assn. coach of the year in 1986-87 with 
the Portland Trail Blazers, is expected to come to Los Angeles later in the 
week to be interviewed for the vacant Clippers' position, team officials 
confirmed Monday. 
</P>
<P>
He would become the only person to meet with Clipper officials about the job 
besides Don Casey, the interim coach since Jan. 19. 
</P>
<P>
Schuler, who could not be reached for comment, spent 2 1/2 seasons with the 
Trail Blazers before being fired on Feb. 18. He joined Golden State as a scout 
for the final months of the season, and had a standing offer to join the 
Warriors as one of Don Nelson's assistant coaches for 1989-90 if he wanted. 
</P>
<P>
A former assistant under Nelson at Milwaukee and Larry Brown at New Jersey, 
Schuler became the ninth coach in NBA history to win 100 games in his first two 
seasons, guiding the Trail Blazers to a 102-62 record (a 62.2 winning 
percentage). But on-going reports of friction with players, especially star 
Clyde Drexler, led to his firing. SCOTT HOWARD-COOPER 
</P>
</TEXT>
